{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480600"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"80"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"80","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/80"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.24,0.02,0.03,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"80"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"80","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/80"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"80"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61971"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44745"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of abdominal bloating, discomfort, increasing constipation, and diminished appetite. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is distended but soft and non-tender. Investigations reveal a CA125 of 25 U/mL (0-35). An abdominal ultrasound shows bilateral multiloculated cysts with septations on both ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI pelvis","Repeat ultrasound and CA125 in three months","Referral to dietitian","Watchful waiting with annual review","Gynaecological oncology referral"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with concerning features for ovarian malignancy. The Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) is calculated as menopausal status (3) \u00d7 ultrasound findings (3) \u00d7 CA125 level (25) = 225. An RMI \u0026gt;200 warrants urgent \u003Cstrong\u003Egynaecological oncology referral\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E would not add significant value to the diagnostic workup. While MRI can characterise ovarian masses, CT chest/abdomen/pelvis is the preferred imaging modality for staging if malignancy is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound and CA125 in three months\u003C/strong\u003E would cause unnecessary delay in management. The current findings already indicate the need for specialist assessment, particularly given the patient\u0027s age and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to dietitian\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying pathology. While the patient has gastrointestinal symptoms, these are likely secondary to the ovarian pathology and require investigation rather than dietary modification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting with annual review\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the concerning clinical features and elevated RMI. Ovarian cancer often presents late, and any delay in investigation could compromise outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of postmenopausal status, bilateral complex ovarian cysts, and symptoms such as bloating and changes in bowel habit raises significant concern for ovarian malignancy, even with a normal CA125. CA125 can be normal in early ovarian cancer and should not be used in isolation to rule out malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A multiloculated ovarian cyst in a postmenopausal woman should raise concern for malignancy regardless of CA125 level.","The Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) combines menopausal status, ultrasound findings, and CA125 to guide specialist referral.","Vague symptoms like bloating and changes in bowel habit may be the only early signs of ovarian cancer."],"references":["The Management of ovarian cysts in postmenopausal women. In: RCOG [online]. 2016 [Accessed 2020 Aug 28] .Available at: https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/green-top-guidelines/gtg_34.pdf.","Jacobs IJ, Menon U, Ryan A, et al. Ovarian cancer screening and mortality in the UK Collaborative Trial of Ovarian Cancer Screening (UKCTOCS): a randomised controlled trial [published correction appears in Lancet. 2016 Mar 5;387(10022):944] [published correction appears in Lancet. 2016 Mar 5;387(10022):944]. Lancet. 2016;387(10022):945-956. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26707054/","Nunes N, Ambler G, Foo X, et al. Comparison of two protocols for the management of asymptomatic postmenopausal women with adnexal tumours - a randomised controlled trial of RMI/RCOG vs Simple Rules. Br J Cancer. 2017;116(5):584-591. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28152542/","Yeoh, M. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Australian Family Physician. 2015;44(1):48\u201352. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"80"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:32:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-06T08:53:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"80"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76474"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}